      "content": "Depreciation calculations can be a bit of a minefield, but don't worry, I'm here to help. The MACRS formula for a 5-year property class is a bit like navigating a goblin-infested cave - you've got to know the right path to take. \n\nFor a 5-year property class, the MACRS formula is:\n\nDepreciation = (Cost - Residual Value) / (Cost - Residual Value) x (1 - (1 / (2^n)))\n\nWhere n is the number of years remaining in the asset's useful life. In this case, n = 5.\n\nHowever, a more straightforward approach is to use the 200% declining balance method, which is like having a goblin guide you through the process. \n\nFor the 200% declining balance method, the annual depreciation is:\n\nAnnual Depreciation = (Cost - Residual Value) x 0.2\n\nBut, you'll need to calculate the annual depreciation for each year, taking into account the asset's remaining useful life. It's a bit like having a goblin whispering in your ear, guiding you through the calculations.\n\nFor example, if the asset's cost is $100,000 and its",
